{"parse":{"title":"Iron Triangle of Health Care","pageid":45213097,"revid":814638282,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>The concept of the <i><b>Iron Triangle of Health Care</b></i> was first introduced in <a href=\"/wiki/William_Kissick\" title=\"William Kissick\">William Kissick\u2019s</a> book, <i>Medicine\u2019s Dilemmas: Infinite Needs Versus Finite Resources</i> in 1994, describing  three competing health care issues: access, quality, and cost containment.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Kissick_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Kissick-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-Niles_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Niles-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>  Each of the vertices represents identical priorities. Increasing or decreasing one results in changes to one or both of the other two. For example, a policy that increases access to health services would lower quality of health care and/or increase cost. The desired state of the triangle, high access and quality with low cost represents value in a health care system.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Carroll_3-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Carroll-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Criticisms_of_the_Iron_Triangle\">Criticisms of the Iron Triangle</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Iron_Triangle_of_Health_Care&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Criticisms of the Iron Triangle\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Critics of the Iron Triangle state that the model is not actually as rigid as its name indicates, but is more dynamic because costs of care are constantly changing. <a href=\"/wiki/Health_care_costs\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Health care costs\">Health care costs</a> change faster than the other two dimensions of the triangle, affecting access to care, which in turn influences quality.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Godfrey_4-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Godfrey-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> Other skeptics argue that the Iron Triangle is not a fixed framework, but an observation and reflection of the current state of health care.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Davis_5-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Davis-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup> In line with <a href=\"/wiki/Clayton_M._Christensen\" title=\"Clayton M. Christensen\">Clayton Christensen\u2019s</a> theory on <a href=\"/wiki/Disruptive_innovation\" title=\"Disruptive innovation\">disruptive innovation</a>, critics of the Iron Triangle believe that health care, particularly in the United States, has not yet been disrupted like fields such as computer production. The belief is that with time and innovation, the current Iron Triangle will be disrupted, and just as the cost of computer production has fallen as quality and access to computers has increased, health care access and quality will rise, and cost will decrease. Critics argue that the Iron Triangle is not a one-size-fits-all model that can be applied to an entire population.<sup id=\"cite_ref-DOJ_6-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-DOJ-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Iron_Triangle_of_Health_Care&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-Kissick-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-Kissick_1-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Kissick, W. (1994). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?id=G038jRhEwRkC&amp;printsec=frontcover&amp;source=gbs_ge_summary_r&amp;cad=0#v=onepage&amp;q&amp;f=false\">\u201cMedicine\u2019s Dilemmas\u201d</a>. New Haven and New London, CT: Yale University Press.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-Niles-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-Niles_2-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Niles, N. (2015). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?id=A0UoAwAAQBAJ&amp;printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&amp;q&amp;f=false\">History of the U.S. Healthcare System</a>. In Basics of the U.S. Health Care System (2nd ed., pp. 12-13). Burlington, Mass: Jones &amp; Bartlett Learning.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-Carroll-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-Carroll_3-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Carroll, A. (October 3, 2012). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://newsatjama.jama.com/2012/10/03/jama-forum-the-iron-triangle-of-health-care-access-cost-and-quality/\">JAMA Forum</a>. Retrieved January 18, 2015.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-Godfrey-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-Godfrey_4-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Godfrey, T. (March 3, 2012). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://pennsquarepost.com/what-is-the-iron-triangle-of-health-care/\">What is the Iron Triangle of Health Care</a>? Retrieved January 18, 2015.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-Davis-5\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-Davis_5-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Davis, L. (October 26, 2012). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.kevinmd.com/blog/2012/10/iron-triangle-health-care-law-observation.html\">The iron triangle of health care is not law, but an observation</a>. Retrieved January 18, 2015.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-DOJ-6\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-DOJ_6-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Department of Justice. (n.d.). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.justice.gov/atr/public/health_care/204694/exec_sum.htm\">Executive Summary: Current Health Care Challenges</a>.\nRetrieved January 18, 2015.</span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n\n<!-- \nNewPP limit report\nParsed by mw1327\nCached time: 20180903165410\nCache expiry: 1900800\nDynamic content: false\nCPU time usage: 0.028 seconds\nReal time usage: 0.040 seconds\nPreprocessor visited node count: 133/1000000\nPreprocessor generated node count: 0/1500000\nPost\u2010expand include size: 368/2097152 bytes\nTemplate argument size: 92/2097152 bytes\nHighest expansion depth: 7/40\nExpensive parser function count: 0/500\nUnstrip recursion depth: 0/20\nUnstrip post\u2010expand size: 3101/5000000 bytes\nNumber of Wikibase entities loaded: 0/400\nLua time usage: 0.003/10.000 seconds\nLua memory usage: 525 KB/50 MB\n-->\n<!--\nTransclusion expansion time report (%,ms,calls,template)\n100.00%   25.007      1 Template:Reflist\n100.00%   25.007      1 -total\n  7.16%    1.791      1 Template:Main_other\n-->\n\n<!-- Saved in parser cache with key enwiki:pcache:idhash:45213097-0!canonical and timestamp 20180903165410 and revision id 814638282\n -->\n</div>"},"langlinks":[],"categories":[{"sortkey":"","*":"Health_economics"}],"links":[{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Clayton M. Christensen"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Disruptive innovation"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Health care costs"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"William Kissick"}],"templates":[{"ns":10,"exists":"","*":"Template:Reflist"},{"ns":10,"exists":"","*":"Template:Main other"},{"ns":828,"exists":"","*":"Module:Check for unknown parameters"}],"images":[],"externallinks":["https://books.google.com/books?id=G038jRhEwRkC&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false","https://books.google.com/books?id=A0UoAwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false","http://newsatjama.jama.com/2012/10/03/jama-forum-the-iron-triangle-of-health-care-access-cost-and-quality/","http://pen